         <abstract>
            <p>The Fraser-Hart variant of the Remez algorithm is used to determine the best rational Chebyshev approximation to a continuous function on an interval. A necessary and sufficient condition for the matrix of the associated linear system to be nonsingular at the solution to the approximation problem is given. It is shown that the Fraser-Hart method may fail even if started arbitrarily close to the solution of the approximation problem. Use of the secant method in place of the Fraser-Hart iteration is also considered.</p>
          </abstract>
